content.text:
The issue was that AnkiDroid's `TemplateManager` was parsing image sources using `java.net.URI` to detect the URI scheme. When encountering a filename containing a `#` (hash) character (e.g., `image#1.png`), `URI` interpreted the `#` as a fragment separator. This caused the filename to be truncated (e.g., to `image`), resulting in a broken image link because the file `image` does not exist.

To fix this, I modified `parseSourcesToFileScheme` in `AnkiDroid/src/main/java/com/ichi2/libanki/TemplateManager.kt`. The updated logic checks if a URI has a fragment. If it does, it checks if a file exists with the fragment appended to the path (restoring the original filename). If such a file exists, it treats the full string as the filename. I also added an optional `fileExists` parameter to the function to facilitate unit testing without relying on the actual filesystem.

I added new test cases to `AnkiDroid/src/test/java/com/ichi2/libanki/TemplateManagerTest.kt` to verify:
1. Filenames with `#` are correctly parsed and converted to `file:///` URIs with encoded `%23`.
2. Real fragments (where the file does not include the fragment part) are still handled correctly (falling back to the path component).

The changes ensure that legacy filenames with `#` are displayed correctly while preserving standard URI behavior for actual fragments.

